  "root_text": {
    "sn47.50:0.1": "Saṁyutta Nikāya 47.50 ",
    "sn47.50:0.2": "5. Amatavagga ",
    "sn47.50:0.3": "Āsavasutta ",
    "sn47.50:1.1": "“Tayome, bhikkhave āsavā. ",
    "sn47.50:1.2": "Katame tayo? ",
    "sn47.50:1.3": "Kāmāsavo, bhavāsavo, avijjāsavo—",
    "sn47.50:1.4": "ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo āsavā. ",
    "sn47.50:1.5": "Imesaṁ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṁ āsavānaṁ pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā. ",
    "sn47.50:2.1": "Katame cattāro? ",
    "sn47.50:2.2": "Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṁ; ",
    "sn47.50:2.3": "vedanāsu …pe… ",
    "sn47.50:2.4": "citte …pe… ",
    "sn47.50:2.5": "dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṁ. ",
    "sn47.50:2.6": "Imesaṁ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṁ āsavānaṁ pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti. ",
    "sn47.50:2.7": "Dasamaṁ. ",
    "sn47.50:2.8": "Amatavaggo pañcamo. ",
    "sn47.50:3.0": "Tassuddānaṁ ",
    "sn47.50:3.1": "Amataṁ samudayo maggo, ",
    "sn47.50:3.2": "Sati kusalarāsi ca; ",
    "sn47.50:3.3": "Pātimokkhaṁ duccaritaṁ, ",
    "sn47.50:3.4": "Mittavedanā āsavena cāti. "
  },
  "translation_text": {
    "sn47.50:0.1": "Linked Discourses 47.50 ",
    "sn47.50:0.2": "5. Freedom From Death ",
    "sn47.50:0.3": "Defilements ",
    "sn47.50:1.1": "“Mendicants, there are these three defilements. ",
    "sn47.50:1.2": "What three? ",
    "sn47.50:1.3": "The defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance. ",
    "sn47.50:1.4": "These are the three defilements. ",
    "sn47.50:1.5": "The four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to give up these three defilements. ",
    "sn47.50:2.1": "What four? ",
    "sn47.50:2.2": "It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of covetousness and displeasure for the world. ",
    "sn47.50:2.3": "They meditate observing an aspect of feelings … ",
    "sn47.50:2.4": "mind … ",
    "sn47.50:2.5": "principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of covetousness and displeasure for the world. ",
    "sn47.50:2.6": "These four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to give up these three defilements.” ",
